Land, Sacred History, and Anti-Zionism -- tPart V. Contemporary Antisemitism: The Unending Threat -- tChapter 12. Zionism through the Internet’s Looking Glass -- tChapter 13. Perspectives on Antisemitism and Anti-Zionism in Contemporary Canada -- tChapter 14. The Delegitimization—and Relegitimization—of Israel -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeading scholars use the lenses of history, sociology, political science, psychology, philosophy, religion, and literature to examine, disentangle, and remove the disguises of the many forms of antisemitism and anti-Zionism that have inhabited or targeted the English-speaking world in the twentieth and twenty-first centuries. Although in principle one can be anti-Zionist without being antisemitic, authors document and trace the numerous parallels and continuities between the hoary tropes attached for centuries to the Jewish people and the more recent vilifications of the Jewish state. They evaluate—and discredit—many of the central claims anti-Zionists have promoted in their relentless effort to delegitimize the Jewish state. They show how mainstream anti-racist communities, courses and texts have ignored—or denied—the antisemitic hatred that pervades much of the Muslim world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAntisemitismxHistoryy21st century. 0aAntisemitismzEurope. 0aAntisemitismzUnited States. 0aArab-Israeli conflicty1993-xInfluence. 0aZionismzUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Religious Intolerance, Persecution & Conflict.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuerbach, Jerold S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishman, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v